We’d look at this using scatter plots with different colours / shapes for the different classes

p-values

We need a way to make quantitative, objective statements about our data. To do this we use p-values: the probability of observing our data, or more extreme, given the null hypothesis.

Focus on scatter plots

The question is whether our line is significantly different from zero

Our null hypothesis is that the line has slope = 0.

Our data certainly don’t look like they came from a model with slope forced = 0

Therefore our data are unlikely given the null hypothesis

How unlikely? We need a probability value

Simulate our null hypothesis

Here we can simulate our null hypothesis using data data that should be unrelated. Notice that the slopes can still on occasion start showing a pattern simply due to chance. But this doesn’t occur very often, i.e. there is a low proability of getting a slope much greater than 0.

P-value for our slope

How likely is the “extreme” slope that we observed given the stochasticity (randomness) of our null hypothesis?

Given a distribution of slopes possible under the null hypothesis, we can calculate the probability of our observed slope

We need also to consider “more extreme” slopes in this calculation and this results in a p-value

If p-value is less than 0.05, then we generally reject the null hypothesis

That is, there is a 1 in 20 chance that our observed value is generated by our null model

Summary

Science is about constructing experiments or designing observations to test your ideas about how the world works

Hypotheses must be falsifiable

Generally we construct null hypotheses against which our alternative hypotheses can be tested

p-values tell us how likely it is our data came from the null hypothesis and therefore allow us to accept or reject it (H0)

Introduction to Hypothesis Testing

An experiment flipping coins

A simple experiment

Question:

-Does adding weight to a coin make it unfair?

-Blu-tac added to head side

We need to construct testable hypotheses

-The null hypothesis

Weighted coin toss

Toss the coin 10 times

What is the hypothesis about how you think your system will behave?

-More likely to get heads

-Less likely to get heads

-Either more or less likely to get heads

What are the corresponding null hypotheses?

-That the coin is fair

Behaviour of a fair coin

The model is a fair 50:50 coin

How do we generate information about how a fair coin behaves?

-Toss an un-weighted coin 10 times and repeat

Behaviour of weighted coin

Compare the weighted coin against the expected behaviour of a fair coin

Question

-How likely is it that our observed coin is fair?

##  [1] 0.001 0.010 0.044 0.117 0.205 0.246 0.205 0.117 0.044 0.010 0.001

Alternative hypothesis

HA: coin is more likely to produce heads

-One-tailed test in right tail

HA: coin is less likely to produce heads

-One-tailed test in left tail

HA: coin is unfair (in either direction)

-Two-tailed test including both left and right tails

P-values

A p-value is the probability of your observed data or more extreme being generated according to the null hypothesis

The less likely your data are, the less likely you would accept the null hypothesis as being true

We generally use a cut-off of p<0.05 to accept the alternative hypothesis

One or two tailed tests refer to where you predict your alternative hypotheses to lie before you do your experiment

If we flip out coin 10 times and it comes up heads 9 times the p-value we get is 0.02148 which is much less than the 0.05 cutoff that is usually selected. So this would mean our data are inconsistent with the null hypothesis that the coin is fair.

Summary

Science is about constructing experiments or designing observations to test your ideas about how the world works

Hypotheses must be falsifiable

Generally we construct null hypotheses against which our alternative hypotheses can be tested

p-values tell us how likely it is our data came from the null hypothesis and therefore allow us to accept or reject it (H0)

Regression

A regression is a statistical analysis used to predict scores on an outcome variable, based on scores on one or multiple predictor variables, a simple regression has one predictor variable and a multiple regression has multiple predictor variables

Regression equation

\[Y = B_0 +B_1X_1 + e\]

Y = a linear function of \(X_1\)

\(B_0\) = intercept = regression constant

\(B_1\) = slope = regression coefficient

e = residual error

Simple regression example

height <- c(163, 185, 155, 195, 168, 198, 200, 146, 179, 160, 180, 170, 190)
weight <- c(65, 85, 70, 120, 73, 100, 103, 50, 81, 64, 90, 78, 71)
plot(weight~height,pch=16)
m1<-lm(weight~height)
abline(m1)

print(m1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = weight ~ height)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       height  
##    -83.2047       0.9313

Thus the regression equation is therefore

\(Y=-83.2047+0.9313(X)\)

or weight = -83.2047 + 0.9313(height)

What this means is that for with every one unit increase in X there is a 0.9313 increase in Y.

In our case it means for every cm increase in height there is a 0.9313 kg increase in weight

The estimate of the intercept is -83.2047, is the predicted score on Y when X = 0.

But that doesn’t make a lot of sense here because it would mean a person who has a height of 0 cm is predicted to weigh -83 kg.

ANOVA - Analysis of Variance

Instead of fitting continuous, measured variables to data (as in regression), many experiments involve exposing experimental material to a range of discrete levels of one or more categorical variables known as factors.

The data here are from an agricultural experiment in which six different insect sprays were tested in many different fields, and the response variable was a count of insects found in each field after spraying.

It is important to understand that regression and analysis of variance (ANOVA) are identical approaches except for the nature of the explanatory variables.

A slightly different question

And why its important to consider the linear covariate when comparing between groups

How do we compare two lines statistically?

Known as:

Analysis of Covariance (ANCOVA) aka a GLM with fixed factors and linear covariates

ANCOVA combines elements from regression and analysis of variance. The response variable is continuous, and there is at least one continuous explanatory variable and at least one categorical explanatory variable.

An alternative dataset

Here, the response variable is Fruit, and we have two explanatory variables in Root and Grazing. Root is continuous whereas Grazing is a factor with two levels.

Questions to ask

How does grazing affect seed production?

-Our expectation is that big plants will produce more seeds than small plants

This result looks counter-intuitive because it shows that the plants that were grazed on by herbivores produced MORE seeds not less than the ungrazed plants!

Why was root diameter recorded?

This was recorded because initial plant size was thought likely to influence fruit production.

-How might this have changed the picture if it were omitted?

Different sized plants were allocated to the two treatments.

The grazed plants were bigger at the outset.

If you compare like with like (e.g. plants at 7mm initial root diameter) it is clear that the ungrazed plants produced more seed than the grazed plants.

Creating an ANCOVA model

For ANCOVA, the most complicated model has different slopes and intercepts for each level of the factor.

Here we have a two-level factor (Grazed and Ungrazed) and we are fitting a linear model with two parameters \(y=B_0+B_1X_1\) so the most complicated mode has four parameters (two slopes and two intercepts).

Testing non-parallel lines

To fit different slopes and intercepts we use the asterisk \(*\) notation:

In R we do this as follows:

model1<-glm(Fruit~Root*Grazing,data=growth)

This shows that initial root size has a massive effect on fruit production, but there is no indication of any difference in the slope of this relationship between the two grazing treatments (Root:GrazingUngrazed) so we remove it.

Testing parallel lines

We now use \(+\) rather than \(*\) in the model formula. This says ‘fit different intercepts for grazed and ungrazed plants, but fit the same slope to both graphs’.

model2<-glm(Fruit~Root+Grazing,data=growth)
summary(model2)

You know when you have got a good model, because every row of the coefficients table has one or more significance stars (three in this case, because the effects are all so strong).

In contrast to our initial interpretation based on mean fruit production, grazing is associated with a 36.103 mg reduction in fruit production.

Parameter Estimates Explained

1. Starting at the top, the first row, as labelled contains an intercept.

It is the intercept for the graph of seed production against root size for the grazing treatment whose factor level comes first in the alphabet. So the intercept is the intercept for the grazed plants.

2. The second row, labelled ‘GrazingUngrazed’, is a difference between two intercepts.

To get the intercept for the ungrazed plants, we need to add 36.103 to the intercept for the grazed plants (-127.829+36.103=-91.726).

3. The third row labelled Root, is a slope: it is the gradient of the graph of seed production against root size, and is the same for both grazed and ungrazed plants.

4. If there had been a significant interaction term, this would have appeared in row four as a difference between the two slopes.

Adding the lines to our plot

We can use these paramaters to fit the two regression lines to our data.

For grazed the line is \(-127.829+23.56(X)\)

For the ungrazed line it is \(-127.829+36.103+23.56(X)\)

growth<-read.csv("ipomopsis.csv",header = T,sep = ",")
#head(growth)
plot(growth$Fruit~growth$Root,bty="l",pch = c(2, 16)[as.numeric(growth$Grazing)],xlab="Initial root diameter",ylab = "Seed Production")
legend("topleft", c("ungrazed","grazed"), pch= c(16,2), bty="n",cex=1.5,lwd=2,lty=NA)
abline(-127.829,23.56)
abline(-127.829+36.103,23.56)

Model Parameters

In a linear model with interactions, the mathematical expression for two regressors is:

\[\hat Y=\hat\beta_0+\hat\beta_1\,X_1+\hat\beta_2\,X_2+\hat\beta_3\, \color{blue}{X_1*X_2}\]

one of the variables \(X_2\) is categorical with factors A and B.

For instance, it could be the variable gender with values M and F coded as 0 and 1. Variable \(X_1\) is a continuous measurement.

For males, \((X_2=0)\)\[\color{blue}{X_1*X_2 = X_1\,*\,0 =0}\] for all male observations

We end up with

\[\hat Y=\hat\beta_0+\hat\beta_1\,X_1\]

, with the intercept being \(\hat\beta_0\) and the slope \(\hat\beta_1\)

For females \((X_2=1)\),

\[\color{blue}{X_1*X_2 = X_1\,*\,1 =X_1}\]

We end up with

\[\hat Y=\hat\beta_0+\hat\beta_1\,X_1+\hat\beta_2\,\color{blue}{1}+\hat\beta_3\, \color{blue}{X_1}\]

with intercept \(\hat\beta_0\) + \(\hat\beta_2\) and slope \(\hat\beta_1\) + \(\hat\beta_3\)

So notice that for each factor, and due to the interaction, you wind up with different intercepts and different slopes.

If there was no interaction, the model would be:

\[\hat Y=\hat\beta_0+\hat\beta_1\,X_1+\hat\beta_2\,X_2\]

And we would obtain one single slope for both M and F, \(\hat\beta_1\) and two different intercepts: \(\hat\beta_0\) for M and \(\hat\beta_0+ \hat\beta_2\) for F.

So the presence of an interaction changes the relationship of the continuous variable \(X_1\) with the predicted values (the slope).

Here we have a significant effect of the interaction term. That means we have to fit two slopes and two intercepts.

The baseline intercept will be \(\hat\beta_0\) and the baseline slope will be \(\hat\beta_1\).

The intercept for the next factor level will be \(\hat\beta_0 + \hat\beta_2\) and the slope for the next factor level will be \(\hat\beta_1 + \hat\beta_3\)

Comparing Models

AIC is a number that is helpful for comparing models as it includes measures of both how well the model fits the data and how complex the model is. The lower the AIC the better. In general a -2 difference in AIC suggests an improvement.

What are interactions?

\(Y = B0 + B1X1+ B2X2 + B3X1*X2\)

The interactive effect between X1 and X2 on Y corresponds to the B3 slope. If B3 is reliable (or “statistically significant”), it means that the effect of X1 on Y depends on the level of X2 (or otherwise, but it’s exactly the same, the effect of X2 on Y depends on the level of X1).

Y is lifetime (an objectively good thing to have more of)

X1 (associated with B1) is the number of cigarettes one smokes per day

X2 (associated with B2) is the quantity of alcohol one consumes per day.

X1*X2 (associated with B3) is their interaction

As smoking has a negative effect on life expectancy (the effect B1 being negative on Y), that means that the more you smoke (as X1 gets more positive), the less you live (Y gets less positive).

As the interactive effect of smoking and drinking on life expectancy is negative (the effect of B3 being negative on Y), this means that the more you drink (the more X2 is positive), the more deleterious cigarettes become (B1 becomes more negative). For instance, each smoked cigarette makes you live 2 minutes less as you drink no alcohol, but if you drink one glass of wine per day, each smoked cigarette makes you live 6 minutes less.
